  Year                     = {2008},

  Abstract                 = {Intrinsic post-zygotic isolation is thought to result primarily from negative epistatic interactions between alleles at different loci from divergent populations (the Dobzhansky-Muller model). Uncovering the nature of these incompatible interactions and identifying the genes involved will enable a better understanding of the mechanisms and processes that lead to speciation. Although significant progress in this area has been made using Drosophila, a wide range of taxa must be studied before a full appreciation of the genetic basis of post-zygotic isolation is achieved. The well-documented Pyrenean hybrid zone between Chorthippus parallelus parallelus and C. p. erythropus was used as a model system to dissect the genetic basis of hybrid male sterility. Suppression subtractive hybridization was employed to identify genes that differ in testes expression between the two subspecies. This approach requires no prior sequence information and is widely applicable to nonmodel taxa. Twenty-one clones identified here show differential expression and represent candidate sterility genes. One of these candidates showed reduced introgression across the hybrid zone relative to neutral expectations. Testis follicle lengths in backcross males fit into two distinct classes, implying that few genes of major effect are contributing to sterility. This distinction is supported by a more direct measure of reproductive fitness, the number of sperm transferred during mating. Two candidate genes showed evidence of an association with sterility in backcrosses. No evidence for a reduction in testes size at the centre of the hybrid zone was detected. The findings contrast with a substantial body of work implying that generally, many D-M incompatibilities contribute to post-zygotic isolation. However, unlike many of the species investigated in these studies, the two subspecies examined in the present study are in the early stages of divergence and display incomplete reproductive isolation. For these reasons, the results presented here may be more relevant to the question of how many, and which genes initially cause speciation.},
